title: For Sale:  BUYER BE AWARE FOR POSSIBLE SCAM!
location: Wayne, NJ, New Jersey, United States
postcontent:
I have a feeling there is a scammer(s) on this site.  

The listings below this posting

- EAGLE ARMS EA-15 UNFIRED SEMI AUTO CARBINE .223CAL
- UZI ACTION ARMS IMPORT B MODEL 9MM CARBINE, XLNT
- FDE SIG SAUER 716 AR10 RIFLE 7.62 NATO AR 10
- N PS90 EARLY GEN 2 FNH P90 GREEN PS-90 P-90

ETC ETC ETC

The reasons I believe that he/she/ is a scammer(s)

1. Those listing are from Gunbroker.com. If you copy & paste the titles on gunbroker, the exact same listings come up from TN, AL..etc. 
(For example: http://www.gunbroker.com/Auction/ViewItem.aspx?Item=393061134)
I haven't contacted the seller on gunbroker but I'm 110% sure that they didn't list it. 

2. If you contact the seller on armslist, he will give excuses about not being able to meet & currently at other locations. He is also willing to ship the firearms directly to YOU. But the firearm(s) will never arrive no matter where you arrange them to be shipped since it's just a scam. (The excuse I got: His mother is very sick and he is currently in FL. He will not able to meet but he will arrange a shipment directly to my location if I paid in advance)

3. Obviously not familiar with NJ gun laws and gun laws in general.

4. If you see something that are not NJ compliant and too good to be true, be careful. 

5. Let's always deal FTF with proper paper works. FID, COE and matching state issued ID

Before you guys do anything, make sure first. Be smart and Safe hunting

title: For Sale:  NHM-91 AK-47 not AK-74 M4 AR-15 - price reduced to sell $799
postcontent:
This listing is a civilian semi-auto variant of the Russian AKM (Chinese Type 56) rifle, the NHM-91 was built to imitate the appearance of the Russian RPK light machine gun. First imported and marketed in the United States in 1991 by ChinaSports Inc. Based on the Russian RPK light machine gun, the NHM features a stronger receiver and a longer, thicker-profile chrome-lined barrel measuring 20 inches (508mm) compared to the 590 mm (23.2 in) of the original RPK, along with a forward-mounted steel bipod. The NHM-91 was equipped from the factory with two 30-round magazines and a 75-round Chinese drum magazine. Like the RPK, the NHM-91 utilizes a heavier-gauge stamped sheet metal receiver built from 1.5mm-thick stamped sheet metal instead of the 1mm thickness typical of a Soviet or Chinese-made AKM, resulting in increased rigidity, heavier weight, and improved overall accuracy. The longer, heavier barrel reduces shot dispersion and gives the NHM-91 a longer sight radius, again resulting in improved accuracy over the typical semi-auto AKM. Trigger pull weight is also lighter than other AK designs, and some users report the rifle capable of 2-2.5 minutes of angle accuracy or better with factory 7.62x39mm ammunition. Stocks on the NHM-91 are of a one-piece thumbhole design with integral pistol grip, and are thicker and longer than the standard AKM/AK-47 buttstock. Made by E.C. Bishop or Boyd and constructed from birch wood or hackberry, the NHM-91 buttstock lacks a separate pistol grip, though the rifle may be retrofitted with a separate buttstock by simply cutting off the lower portion of the stock and grip with a band saw, then fitting a new pistol grip. Like its RPK counterpart, the NHM-91 does not come equipped from the factory with a bayonet lug. However, the front of the barrel is threaded and capped off with a thread protector welded onto the threads. By removing the thread protector, a muzzle brake can be fitted. Factory NHM-91 rifles were manufactured with a rivet in the magazine release button, preventing use of some Soviet or German-made AKM or AK-47 magazines. Instead, special magazines with a modified tang were manufactured by Norinco for the NHM-91. Since the sunset of the 1994 Public Safety and Recreational Firearms Use Protection Act, removal of the rivet in the magazine release allows use of any and all AKM, RPK, or AK-47 magazines.

I will include 1 x 30 round mags for the $699

title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson - 38 Special - 6 shot British service revolver
postcontent:
Smith & Wesson - 38 S&W CTG converted to 38 Special - 6 shot revolver, This started out as a British service revolver. When the British were hurting for guns early in WW II, we supplied them with some .38 S&W CTG  revolvers. BNP = Birmingham Nitro Proof (that's Birmingham, England) was added to the gun after WW2 when it was sold surplus by the Brits to dealers. The dealers had to have these guns proofed before they could be sold to the British public. The other markings are also British proof marks.  Numbers on barrel, frame & cylinder match, has original grips, it is missing the lanyard ring,  (7694xx) 1940-1942

title: For Sale:  Browning Superposed Pigeon 12 ga 32" 1967
postcontent:
An excellent condition Browning Superposed model 12 gauge with 32 inch barrels in the Browning luggage case. S7 suffix serial number, indicating 1967 manufacture.

I see no evidence that the gun was built with salt-cured wood. See the last several photos. There is no rust or sign of stains where the stock meets the action. The stock bolt and recoil pad screws are not rusted. The receiver serial number is stamped in the stock and written on the black stock spacer. I don't know if that's evidence that the stock is the original one or if factory replacements for salt wood were similarly marked. I'm unable to remove the screw through the forened to examine the metal underneath, but see no signs of runs anywhere around the forened.

The gun has been used, but remains in better than excellent condition. The bluing on the barrels is 100% except for a small rub mark from the forend that results from take-down. See photo 26.

The wood is solid, with good finish and no cracks or chips or problems. The checkering is good, with no depressions or wear. There's hardly a mark to be found on the forend. It remains in near new condition. The screw on the left side of the forend shows some wear upon close inspection. It's not major, but I'd just say that the screw slot is not perfect. See photo 38. The buttstock shows some small marks, but no major detractions. The bottom of the pistol grip has a mark that's about 1/4 wide (photo 52). There's a small rough spot on the right side of the trigger guard, right next to the metal and a tiny dent that measures less than 1/8" across right behind the tang (photo 53). Lastly, to the rear of the top tang, there's five small lines in the wood, actually under the finish, suggesting this escaped notice at the factory. Barely visible in photo 47. You have to hold the stock at the right angle to see this, else you may never notice.

The recoil pad is in good condition, pliable and not heavily worn. It has been off, and the screw holes are visible.

The length of pull is 14 1/4 inches, with an overall length of 49 1/4 inches.

The receiver looks good. I see no scratches, rubs, stains, finish wear, or marks on the receiver. The only external sign of wear is where the safety/barrel selector rubs on the tang, as shown in photos 11 and 12, and to the gold plating on the trigger. The action is clean, feels solid and locks securely.

The bores and chambers are mirror-bright throughout. The upper barrel measures 0.684" at the muzzle and the lower measures 0.703" which I believe is extra full and improved/modified choke. The rib is 16 mm / 0.635" wide. There's an ivory middle bead and large ivory front bead.

The Browning case is made by Hartmann and is in excellent condition. There's few marks on the outside, just some wear to the stitching around the perimeter. The inside is nice and clean overall, just showing some darkening where the breech end of the barrels rests (photo 55). There's one key.

The shotgun weighs about 8 1/4 lbs. The case weighs close to 9 lbs
